<paragraph id="8BDB36C8FF947C3DC0E7F99EFA82F966" blockId="7.[151,1436,1584,2036]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B39FF947C3DC0E7F99EFEDBF9C9" author="Clarke, C. B." box="[151,325,1584,1610]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" pagination="62 - 73" refId="ref5708" refString="unclassifiable? Taxon 51: 259 - 279. Clarke, C. B. (1884) Acanthaceae. In J. D. Hooker, Flora of British India 4: 387 - 558. L. Reeve &amp; Co, London. Clarke, C. B. (1908). In C. C. Hosseus, Die aus Siam bekannten Acanthaceen. Botanische Jahrbucher 41: 62 - 73. Desmond, R. (1992) The European Discovery of the Indian Flora. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, and Oxford University" type="journal article" year="1884">Clarke (1884)</bibRefCitation>
described this species under the name 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D4BFF947C3DC342F99FFBE0F9C9" authorityName="C. B. Clarke" authorityYear="1884" box="[818,1150,1585,1610]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Strobilanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="phyllocaulos">
<emphasis id="B910EADAFF947C3DC342F99FFBE0F9C9" box="[818,1150,1585,1610]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Strobilanthes phyllocaulos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as he had not seen the material of 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D4BFF947C3DC152F9F9FD83F9F3" box="[290,541,1623,1648]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Strobilanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spicata">
<emphasis id="B910EADAFF947C3DC152F9F9FD83F9F3" box="[290,541,1623,1648]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Strobilanthes spicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at CAL. He cited 
<specimenCount id="9D62FD41FF947C3DC28CF9F9FC07F9F2" box="[764,921,1623,1649]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" type="generic" typeStatus="syntypes">two syntypes</specimenCount>
for 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D4BFF947C3DC3BCF9F9FB1DF9F3" authorityName="C. B. Clarke" authorityYear="1884" box="[972,1155,1623,1648]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Strobilanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="phyllocaulos">
<emphasis id="B910EADAFF947C3DC3BCF9F9FB1DF9F3" box="[972,1155,1623,1648]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">S. phyllocaulos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, collections by himself and Hooker and Thomson, of which we have selected Hooker and Thompson 1987 as 
<typeStatus id="54DF886AFF947C3DC4DBF9D0FA86F91B" box="[1195,1304,1662,1688]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">lectotype</typeStatus>
as it is the most complete material Clarke had available when preparing the protogue. There are 
<specimenCount id="9D62FD41FF947C3DC4DDF90AFAD2F93D" box="[1197,1356,1700,1726]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" type="generic" typeStatus="syntypes">two syntypes</specimenCount>
of the earlier species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D4BFF947C3DC13CF965FE22F966" box="[332,444,1739,1765]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Strobilanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spicata">S. spicata</taxonomicName>
at CAL and the one labelled 
<emphasis id="B910EADAFF947C3DC365F965FCF4F967" box="[789,874,1739,1764]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Simons</emphasis>
429 is here selected as the 
<typeStatus id="54DF886AFF947C3DC4D9F965FA86F966" box="[1193,1304,1739,1765]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">lectotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37E6543FF947C3DC0B6F95CFD6DF877" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BDB36C8FF947C3DC0B6F95CFD6DF877" blockId="7.[151,1436,1584,2036]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName id="4C644D4BFF947C3DC0B6F95CFE21F888" box="[198,447,1778,1803]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Strobilanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spicata">
<emphasis id="B910EADAFF947C3DC0B6F95CFE21F888" box="[198,447,1778,1803]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Strobilanthes spicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is apparently endemic to the Khasi hills of Meghalaya but is not easily separated from 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D4BFF947C3DC0A8F8B7FE05F8B1" authority="Diels" authorityName="Diels" authorityYear="1912" box="[216,411,1816,1842]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Strobilanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="forrestii">
<emphasis id="B910EADAFF947C3DC0A8F8B7FECBF8B1" box="[216,341,1817,1842]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">S. forrestii</emphasis>
Diels
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F3737658FF947C3DC195F8B6FDB1F8B1" box="[485,559,1816,1842]" name="China" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">China</collectingCountry>
. Both have a bent corolla, pubescent on the exterior and a calyx in which one lobe in fruit is noticeably longer than the others. However, they are probably best maintained as distinct species as they are geographically separated and the leaves of Indian 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D4BFF947C3DC395F8C8FBC2F8FC" box="[997,1116,1894,1919]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Strobilanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spicata">
<emphasis id="B910EADAFF947C3DC395F8C8FBC2F8FC" box="[997,1116,1894,1919]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">S. spicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very shortly petiolate, more or less tomentose and serrate whereas those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D4BFF947C3DC377F823FC1CF825" authorityName="Diels" authorityYear="1912" box="[775,898,1933,1958]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Strobilanthes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="forrestii">
<emphasis id="B910EADAFF947C3DC377F823FC1CF825" box="[775,898,1933,1958]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">S. forrestii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are sessile, merely pilose and often subentire or weakly dentate. These differences, however, are not very substantial. A photograph is provided to facilitate comparison between these two species (
<figureCitation id="135F2A4DFF947C3DC21AF874FD78F877" box="[618,742,2010,2036]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1163,1187]" captionTargetId="figure-35@8.[500,1086,181,1141]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6A. Lectotype of Strobilanthes spicata T. Anderson." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4929027" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4929027/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Figure 6B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
